  "action_title": "Use humans to assist migrating amphibians across roads",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nTwo studies (including one replicated study) in Italy and the UK found that despite assisting toads across roads during breeding migrations, 64\u201370% of populations declined over 6\u201310 years.\nOne study in the UK \u00a0found that despite assisting toads across roads during breeding migrations, at 7% of sites over 500 toads were still killed on roads.\nFive studies in Germany, the UK and Italy found that large numbers of amphibians were moved across roads by patrols. Numbers ranged from 7,532 toads moved before and after breeding to half a million moved during breeding migrations annually. In the UK, there were over 400 patrols\u00a0and 71 patrols spent an average of 90 person-hours moving toads and had been active for up to 10 years."
}

tools_called.args:
{"query":"What actions can be taken to mitigate the impacts of roads on amphibian populations?","summary":"Several actions can be taken to mitigate the impacts of roads on amphibian populations. Two studies in Germany indicated that closing roads during seasonal amphibian migration, sometimes combined with assisted crossings and barrier fences, protected many amphibians from being killed during breeding migrations [842].

Another common intervention is the installation of culverts or tunnels. Six of seven studies found that this significantly decreased amphibian road deaths, although one study noted this was only the case when barrier fencing was also installed [884]. The use of these crossings by amphibians was confirmed in 15 of 24 studies, with usage rates varying by species and culvert design. Factors influencing usage include culvert diameter, length, lighting, substrate, and the presence of water [884]. However, some culvert designs, such as those with vertical entry chutes or condensation from steel, can cause high mortality. One study also found that thousands of amphibians were still killed on the road even with culverts present [884].

Using humans to physically assist migrating amphibians across roads has also been studied. Despite these efforts, two studies in Italy and the UK observed population declines of 64–70% over 6–10 years [784]. Furthermore, one UK study found that at 7% of assisted sites, over 500 toads were still killed on the roads [784]. These patrols can involve significant effort, with one case noting an average of 90 person-hours spent by patrols to move amphibians [784].","action_ids":["842","884","784"]}

